<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900706-0070</DOCNO><DOCID>900706-0070.</DOCID><HL>   Coal Mining Firm,   Dairy Face Fines   On Safety Charges   ----   By Albert R. Karr   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/06/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   LABOR T.LBT</CO><GV>LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Labor Department proposed fines of$508,000 against Pyro Mining Co., a coal-mining concern, and$1 million against Johanna Farms, a dairy and citrus-productpackaging firm, on charges of safety violations.   The department's Mine Safety and Health Administrationcited Pyro Mining's William Station mine in Union County,Ky., for 121 violations, including alleged electrical-safetyviolations and failure to make required safety examinations.</LP><TEXT>   The mine-safety agency said the proposed fine stemmed froma methane explosion at the mine last September that killed 10people. The agency said the explosion occurred afterexplosive methane gas accumulated without being detected.   The penalties would be a record amount for the mine-safetyagency, four times the largest fine assessed for any previoussingle mine accident. The violations were &quot;flagrant&quot; andshowed Pyro Mining's &quot;negligence,&quot; William Tattersall,assistant secretary of labor for the agency, said.   Separately, the department's Occupational Safety andHealth Administration cited Johanna Farms, Flemington, N.J.,for violating safety and record-keeping standards. Thecompany, which packages dairy products, citrus juices andyogurt, is a unit of John LaBatt Ltd., a holding companybased in North London, Ontario.   Johanna Farms was cited for 197 willful instances offailure to report injuries and illnesses and for 23 instancesof allowing workers to be exposed to unguarded machinery.OSHA said 34 employees also were exposed to unguardedsprockets and chains, among other safety violations. GerardScannell, assistant secretary of labor for OSHA, said thecompany suffered &quot;a serious breakdown in its internal safetyand health program.&quot;   Pyro Mining has 30 days to contest its citations andproposed fine before the independent Federal Mine Safety andHealth Review Commission. Johanna Farms has 15 days tocontest its citations and fine before the Occupational Safetyand Health Review Commission.</TEXT></DOC>